# Code Conventions

## Arrow functions
Use arrow functions whenever possible, including for components, handlers, and utilities.

```ts
// BAD
function getUser(id: string) { /* ... */ }

// GOOD
const getUser = (id: string) => { /* ... */ };
```

## Translations
Use `useTranslations` without a namespace argument. Always pass the full key path to `t`.

```tsx
// BAD
const t = useTranslations('issues.detail');
t('title');

// GOOD
const t = useTranslations();
t('issues.detail.title');
```

## Type safety
Stick to strict type safety. When a set of literal values is needed, declare a `const` assertion and derive the type from it.

```ts
// GOOD
const ISSUE_STATUSES = ['open', 'in_progress', 'resolved'] as const;
type IssueStatus = (typeof ISSUE_STATUSES)[number];
```

Avoid `any`, non-null assertions (`!`), and untyped casts. Prefer narrowing and discriminated unions.

## Destructure mutation hooks
Always destructure the return of any hook that wraps `useMutation` (whether it's a custom `use*` hook or an inline `useMutation`) at the top of the component. Rename via `mutate: verbName` when the generic `mutate` would be ambiguous. Never write `someMutation.mutate(...)`, `someMutation.isPending`, `someMutation.variables`, etc.

```tsx
// BAD
const createMutation = useCreateIssue(locale);
createMutation.mutate({ /* ... */ });
if (createMutation.isPending) { /* ... */ }

// GOOD
const { mutate: createIssue, isPending } = useCreateIssue(locale);
createIssue({ /* ... */ });
```

## Destructure `useForm` and extract typed default values
- Destructure the object returned by `@mantine/form`'s `useForm` (mirrors how query hooks are consumed).
- Never inline `initialValues` inside the `useForm({ ... })` argument. Declare a `defaultValues` const and a matching form type, then pass `useForm<FormType>({ initialValues: defaultValues, ... })`.
- Prefer declaring the type first when any field needs a non-literal type (e.g. `IssueType` instead of the inferred `"ticket"`). Otherwise `type FormValues = typeof defaultValues` is fine.

```tsx
// BAD
const form = useForm({
  initialValues: {
    title: "",
    issue_type: "ticket" as "bug" | "ticket",
  },
});
form.onSubmit((values) => { /* ... */ });
form.getInputProps("title");

// GOOD
type CreateIssueFormValues = {
  title: string;
  issue_type: IssueType;
};

const defaultValues: CreateIssueFormValues = {
  title: "",
  issue_type: IssueTypes.TASK,
};

const { onSubmit, getInputProps, values, reset } = useForm<CreateIssueFormValues>({
  initialValues: defaultValues,
  validate: { /* ... */ },
});
```

## Centralise frequently-used literal unions
If a small set of literal strings is used across multiple files (e.g. issue type, user role, status slug), declare the runtime values with `as const` in a single module and derive the type from that constant. Import the constant (not the raw string) everywhere it's used, including form defaults, UI option lists, zod schemas, and service-layer defaults.

Naming convention (apply everywhere `as const` is used to model a literal union):
- The const is named in PascalCase, plural: `IssueTypes`, `UserRoles`, `IssueSortDirections`.
- The derived type is the singular form: `IssueType`, `UserRole`, `IssueSortDirection`.
- Property keys inside the const are `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`; the literal values stay as-is (the actual string used at runtime / stored in the DB).
- A companion tuple of values, when needed (e.g. for `z.enum`), uses the same plural PascalCase plus a `Values` suffix: `IssueTypeValues`.

```ts
// src/features/issues/issueTypeUtils.ts
export const IssueTypes = { BUG: "bug", TASK: "ticket" } as const;
export type IssueType = (typeof IssueTypes)[keyof typeof IssueTypes];
export const IssueTypeValues = [IssueTypes.BUG, IssueTypes.TASK] as const;

// BAD
issue_type: "ticket" as "bug" | "ticket";
z.enum(["bug", "ticket"]);

// GOOD
issue_type: IssueTypes.TASK;
z.enum(IssueTypeValues);
```

## Extract hooks from cluttered components
If a component file accumulates non-trivial logic (effects, derived state, mutations, handlers), extract it into a custom hook placed in the feature's existing `hooks/` folder (e.g. `src/features/<feature>/hooks/`). Keep the component file focused on JSX + wiring.
